							<h1>Chinatowns across North America and the World </h1>
                                                        <audio src="/audio/en/world_chinatown.mp3">
                                                            Recording of Chinatowns across North America and the World article
                                                        </audio>
								<p>The precursor to modern Chinatowns was the Chinese enclave community in Manilla, established in 1594. Early American Chinatowns, such as the one in Los Angeles, were a destination for Chinese descendants, after migration increased during the California Gold Rush of the 1850s. <br>
								At first, Chinese enclaves were full almost exclusively of people of Han Chinese origin and descent, though the Chicago Chinatown was originally a mostly Cantonese enclave. That said, Chinatowns around the country have diversified over the past few decades. There are many Chinese characteristics in Chinatown communities, and many stores that are located in districts use Chinese writing in their signs. Nowadays, most Chinatowns in America have both Chinese and English language signs.<br>
								Chinatowns are common destinations for Chinese and other Asian cuisines. Some Chinatowns that incorporated Singaporean and Thai food developed their own blends which make Chinatowns more flexible for food lovers. </p>
